article.headline: Mazzante limited to four points, but Lions win
article.linkText: Wright leads No. 7 Penn State past Iowa
article.story:
IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Penn State made its strongest case yet
that there's more to the team than Kelly Mazzante.

Mazzante, the Big Ten's career scoring leader, had a career-low
four points against Iowa on Sunday, but the seventh-ranked Lady
Lions got 24 points from Tanisha Wright and played outstanding
defense in winning 70-58.

"This team just can't depend on Kelly," said Wright, who was
10-of-17 from the field and added six rebounds, three assists and
two steals. "We've been saying that for three years now. We've
been trying to get to that point, and this year we're really at
that point.

"If she has a bad night, there's other people on this team that
can step up. It's not just myself."

Others certainly came through in this one to help Penn State
(21-4, 13-1) stay tied with Purdue for first place in the Big Ten.

Jess Strom added 17 points and five assists, Jess Brungo had 15
points, including three 3-pointers, and 10 rebounds, and freshman
Reicina Russell grabbed 17 rebounds.

"Obviously Kelly does a great job and tonight she had one of
her tough nights," Penn State coach Rene Portland said. "I think
the kids know she'll be back, but it also gives confidence to
everybody else. I'm just glad they kept their poise on a tough
night for her."

Mazzante, averaging 21.1 points, went 2-for-12 and fouled out in
just 22 minutes. She missed her first five shots, picked up her
second foul at the 7:41 mark of the first half and never got
untracked.

Her previous low was six points as a sophomore in 2001-02. Her
low this season had been 12.

Kristi Faulkner led Iowa (15-10, 9-5) with 18 points. The
Hawkeyes shot only 31.7 percent, had trouble running their offense
against Penn State's trapping defense and were held to a season low
for points.

"If you would have told me that Kelly Mazzante would score four
points and play 22 minutes and we lose this game by 12, I probably
would have doubted you strongly," Iowa coach Lisa Bluder said.

"But Tanisha Wright was outstanding. I think more than that,
though, their defense just really took us out of it. They played a
very physical style and that's the way the officials allowed the
game to be called and we didn't make the adjustments. We were more
concerned about what wasn't getting called instead of adapting to
that."

Brungo helped Penn State take control after Iowa drew to 39-37
on Johanna Solverson's layup early in the second half. A 3 by
Brungo started a 7-0 run that made it 46-37, and Wright's jumper
from the left side gave Penn State a 48-40 lead.

Tiffany Reedy's reverse layup pulled Iowa within six, but the
Hawkeyes got no closer. Strom scored five points and Brungo made
another 3 in an 8-2 run that stretched the lead to 56-44. The Lady
Lions were ahead by double digits the rest of the way.

Penn State withstood Mazzante's struggles in the first half by
consistently beating the Hawkeyes down the floor for layups.
Thirteen of Penn State's 15 first-half field goals were layups and
the Lady Lions outscored Iowa 20-0 on fastbreak points in taking a
33-27 halftime lead.

"I think we got our running game going," Wright said. "Our
posts were getting some good rebounds and were kicking it out. Not
just kicking it out toward the back but looking ahead. That was the
point where we were able to get the ball advanced and keep going."

Jamie Cavey added 14 points for Iowa, while Jennie Lillis,
averaging 16.5, managed only nine on 2-for-16 shooting in her final
regular season home game.
